=== 13.1 Rotary Positional Encoding (RoPE)

The sinusoidal positional encoding in Chapter 5 adds a fixed signal to each embedding *before* the attention layers.
*RoPE* (Su et al., 2021) takes a different approach: it encodes position directly into the query and key vectors inside each attention layer by rotating them.

For a query vector stem:[q] at position stem:[m] and key vector stem:[k] at position stem:[n]:

stem:[\langle R_m q,\; R_n k \rangle = \langle q, R_{n-m} k \rangle]

where stem:[R_\theta] is a block-diagonal rotation matrix.
The dot product depends only on the *relative* position stem:[n - m], not the absolute positions.
This gives the model a natural sense of distance between tokens.

*Key advantages of RoPE:*

- Generalises to sequences longer than those seen during training.
- No extra parameters — the rotation is deterministic.
- Compatible with linear attention variants.
- Used in LLaMA, Mistral, Qwen, and most open-weight models.

In 2D, a rotation by stem:[\theta] looks like:

stem:[R_\theta = \begin{bmatrix} \cos\theta & -\sin\theta \\ \sin\theta & \cos\theta \end{bmatrix}]

For a stem:[d]-dimensional vector, stem:[d/2] independent 2D rotations are applied to pairs of dimensions.

[[fig-ch13-rope]]
.RoPE rotates query and key vectors by position — their dot product captures relative distance
image::images/ch13_rope.png[Two vectors rotating by different angles, with the relative angle between them labelled as the positional signal.]
